    <chapter xml:id="Week-03">
      <title>Week 3: Jan. 25-29</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
            This week, we explore a few more mathematical preliminaries. We first dive into the things we can do with sets.
            Then, we move to relations and equivalence relations, foundational notions both for future work in matheamtics (even in this class).
            Our first portfolio problem is due on Wednesday; this is really an introduction to <m>\LaTeX</m>, the language in which we'll write our mathematical portfolio work.
            Also due Wednesday is an Edfinity assignment over <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-sets.html">Section 0.3</url>, and we'll take a weekly quiz over the notes on Friday.
          </p>
      </introduction>
      <section xml:id="Jan-25">
        <title>Jan. 25: Operations on Sets</title>
        
        <introduction>
          
          <assemblage>
            <title>Motivating Questions</title>
            <p>
            <statement>
            Here are some questions we'll consider.
            <ol>
              <li>What is the power set of a set?</li>
              <li>What is the cardinality of a set?</li> 
              <li>How do we calculate union and intersection of one or more sets?</li>
              <li>What are the complement and set difference operations?</li>
              <li>What is the Cartesian product of two sets?</li>
            </ol>
            </statement>
            </p>
            
          </assemblage>
          
          
            
            
           
          </introduction>
          
          <subsection>
            <title>Outline</title>
            
            <p>
            Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-sets.html#xIo">Section 0.3</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
            </p>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Operations</title>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Subset and Power Set</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                    A set <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m> if every element of <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m>.
                    We call the set of all subsets of <m>A</m> the <term>power set</term>
                    <idx><h>power set</h></idx>
                of <m>A</m>, and write it <m>\pow(A)</m>.
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <activity>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Consider the set <m>A = \set{1,\triangle,\set{5}}</m>.
                    Calculate <m>\pow(A)</m>.
                    What is <m>\pow(\emptyset)</m>?
                  </p>
                </statement>
                </activity>
                
                <assemblage>
                  <title>Cardinality</title>
                  <p>
                    <statement>
                     The number of elements in a set <m>A</m> is called its <term>cardinality</term>, denoted <m>\card{A}</m>.
                     If <m>\card{A}</m> is a finite number, we say <m>A</m> is <term>finite</term>. Otherwise, we say <m>A</m> is infinite.
                    </statement>
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                <activity>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Find the cardinality of the following sets.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>A=\set{20, 21, \ldots, 35}</m></li>
                      <li><m>T = \set{1,\set{2,3},\set{4},\emptyset}</m></li>
                      <li><m>X = \set{2, 4, 6, 8, 6, 4, 2}</m></li>
                      <li><m>\pow(\set{1,\triangle,\set{5}})</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </activity>
                
                <assemblage>
                  <title>Union and Intersection</title>
                  <p>
                    <statement>
                      Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets.
                      The <term>union</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, denoted <m>A\cup B</m>, is the set containing all elements <m>x</m> which are in <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> (or both).
                      The intersection <m>A\cap B</m> is the set of all elements of <m>x</m> in both <m>A</m> <emph>and</emph> <m>B</m>.
                    </statement>
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                <p permid="SNP">
                  Often when dealing with sets,
                  we will have some understanding as to what <q>everything</q> is.
                  Perhaps we are only concerned with natural numbers.
                  In this case we would say that our
                  <term>universe</term> is <m>\N</m>.
                  <idx><h>universe set</h></idx>
                  Sometimes we denote this universe by <m>\U</m>.
                  Given this context,
                  we might wish to speak of all the elements which are
                  <em>not</em> in a particular set.
                  We say <m>B</m> is the <term>complement</term>
                      <idx><h>complement of a set</h></idx>
                  of <m>A</m>, and write,
                  <me permid="Czy">
                    B = \bar A
                  </me>
                  when <m>B</m> contains every element not contained in <m>A</m>.
                  So, if our universe is <m>\{1, 2,\ldots, 9, 10\}</m>,
                  and <m>A = \{2, 3, 5, 7\}</m>,
                  then <m>\bar A = \{1, 4, 6, 8, 9,10\}</m>.
                </p>
                
                <p permid="yUY">
                  Of course we can perform more than one operation at a time.
                  For example, consider
                  <me permid="iGH">
                    A \cap \bar B
                  </me>.
                </p>
            
                <p permid="fch">
                  This is the set of all elements which are both elements of <m>A</m> and not elements of <m>B</m>.
                  What have we done?
                  We've started with <m>A</m> and removed all of the elements which were in <m>B</m>.
                  Another way to write this is the
                  <term>set difference</term>:
                      <idx><h>set</h><h>difference</h></idx>
                      <idx><h>difference of sets</h></idx>
                  <me permid="ONQ">
                    A \cap \bar B = A \setminus B
                  </me>.
                </p>
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>A = \set{2,3,4,5}</m> and <m>B=\set{1,5}</m> be subsets of the universe <m>\mathcal{U} = \set{1,2,3,4,5}</m>.
                      List the elements of the following sets.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>{\bar A}</m></li>
                      <li><m>{\bar B}</m></li>
                      <li><m>A\cup B</m></li>
                      <li><m>A\cap B</m></li>
                      <li><m>A\setminus B</m></li>
                      <li><m>B\setminus A</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                  
                  <assemblage>
                    <title>Cartesian Product</title>
                    <p>
                      <statement>
                       The last way we'll combine sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> involves making ordered pairs.
                       We say the <term>Cartesian product</term> of <m>A</m> with <m>B</m> is the set of all ordered pairs <m>(a,b)</m> in which <m>a\in A</m> and <m>b\in B</m>.
                       That is, <m>A \times B = \{(a,b) \st a \in A \wedge b \in B\}</m>.
                      </statement>
                    </p>
                  </assemblage>
                  
                  <activity>
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Let <m>A = \set{\square,\triangle,\bigcirc}</m> and <m>B=\set{2,3}</m>.
                        List the elements of either <m>A\times B</m> or <m>B\times A</m> (your choice). Do the two products have the same elements? Explain. Then calculate <m>\card{A\times A}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </statement>
                    </activity>
                
                
            </subsubsection>
            
            
            
